No, Mantine doesn't ship any built-in `clamp()` helper for theming — the `clamp` exports in `@mantine/hooks` are a JS number-clamping utility, unrelated to CSS `clamp()`.

That said, it works fine in practice because Mantine theme tokens (`fontSizes`, `spacing`, `radius`, `lineHeights`, etc.) are plain strings that get emitted as CSS custom properties. Since `clamp()` is just valid CSS, you can drop it straight into the theme:

```ts
import { createTheme } from '@mantine/core';

export const theme = createTheme({
  fontSizes: {
    xl: 'clamp(1.5rem, 1rem + 2vw, 3rem)',
  },
  spacing: {
    lg: 'clamp(1rem, 0.5rem + 1.5vw, 2.5rem)',
  },
});
```

This becomes `--mantine-font-size-xl: clamp(...)` etc., and any component reading that variable gets fluid sizing for free. Same trick works on individual component style props (`fz="clamp(1rem, 2vw, 2rem)"`) or in a `styles`/CSS module override — Mantine doesn't validate these strings, so anything CSS accepts, it accepts.

One caveat: Mantine's own `rem()`/`em()` conversion helpers (used internally and in `theme.other` conventions) won't parse a `clamp()` string, so if you need rem-based scaling with the user's font-size setting respected, write the clamp's rem values by hand rather than piping through `rem()`.

